[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lime</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Lime
<hw>Lime</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>lime</ets>; of Persian
origin. See <er>Lemon</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>
<def>The fruit of the <spn>Citrus aurantifolia</spn>, allied to the
lemon, but greener in color; also, the tree which bears it.</def>
<note>The term <ex>lime</ex> was formerly also applied to variants of
the closely related <contr>citron</contr>, of which there are two
varieties, <spn>Citrus Medica</spn>, var. <varn>acida</varn> which is
intensely sour, and the <col><b>sweet lime</b></col> (<spn>Citrus
Medica</spn>, var. <varn>Limetta</varn>) which is only slightly sour.
See <er>citron</er>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The color of the lime{1}, a
yellowish-green.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lime</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Lime
<hw>Lime</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>l⟦imac⟧m</ets>; akin to D.
<ets>lijm</ets>, G. <ets>leim</ets>, OHG. <ets>l⟦imac⟧m</ets>, Icel.
<ets>l⟦imac⟧m</ets>, Sw. <ets>lim</ets>, Dan. <ets>liim</ets>, L.
<ets>limus</ets> mud, <ets>linere</ets> to smear, and E.
<ets>loam</ets>. ⟦root⟧126. Cf. <er>Loam</er>, <er>Liniment</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Birdlime.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Like the <qex>lime</qex>⟦br⟧
That foolish birds are caught with.</q>
<rj><qau>Wordsworth.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Oxide of calcium,
<chform>CaO</chform>; the white or gray, caustic substance, usually
called <altname>quicklime</altname>, obtained by calcining limestone or
shells, the heat driving off carbon dioxide and leaving lime. It
develops great heat when treated with water, forming <er>slaked
lime</er>, and is an essential ingredient of cement, plastering, mortar,
etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Lime is the principal constituent of limestone, marble,
chalk, bones, shells, etc.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Caustic lime</b></col>, <cd>Calcium hydroxide or slaked
lime; also, in a less technical sense, calcium oxide or quicklime.</cd>
-- <col><b>Lime burner</b></col>, <cd>one who burns limestone, shells,
etc., to make lime.</cd> -- <col><b>Lime pit</b></col>, <cd>a limestone
quarry.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Lime rod</b></col>, <col><b>Lime
twig</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a twig smeared with birdlime; hence, that
which catches; a snare.</cd> <au>Chaucer.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lime</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Lime
<hw>Lime</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Limed</conjf> <pr>(l⟦imac⟧md)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Liming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. AS. <ets>gel⟦imac⟧man</ets>
to glue or join together. See <er>Lime</er> a viscous substance.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To smear with a viscous substance, as
birdlime.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These twigs, in time, will come to be <qex>limed</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To entangle; to insnare.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We had <qex>limed</qex> ourselves⟦br⟧
With open eyes, and we must take the chance.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To treat with lime, or oxide or hydrate of calcium;
to manure with lime; <as>as, to <ex>lime</ex> hides for removing the
hair; to <ex>lime</ex> sails in order to whiten them; to <ex>lime</ex>
the lawn to decrease acidity of the soil.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Land may be improved by draining, marling, and
<qex>liming</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir J. Child.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To cement.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Who gave his blood to
<xex>lime</xex> the stones together.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj></p>

<p><ent>lime</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
